1
00:01:24,720 --> 00:01:29,510
Dear hussars and ISAF Team 7.
This is it.

2
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:35,073
Is the task important?
Is it still relevant for us Danes?

3
00:01:35,240 --> 00:01:40,155
These are obvious questions
that you may be asking yourselves.

4
00:01:40,320 --> 00:01:43,915
Your predecessors
in Helmand have pushed forward -

5
00:01:44,080 --> 00:01:47,993
- and made a huge effort
in aid of a civilian population -

6
00:01:48,160 --> 00:01:51,789
- that has lived
under miserable conditions.

7
00:01:51,960 --> 00:01:57,478
For this, several of our colleagues
have paid a high price.

8
00:01:57,640 --> 00:02:01,519
It's your duty to continue
unhesitatingly in their footsteps -

9
00:02:01,680 --> 00:02:06,196
- now that your government has
charted its political course.

10
00:02:26,840 --> 00:02:30,116
- Yes.
- When are you going to Jutland?

11
00:02:30,280 --> 00:02:35,718
To Jutland?
That will be on ... Thursday.

12
00:02:38,680 --> 00:02:43,708
- And the exercise will last for ...?
- Ten days.

13
00:02:55,440 --> 00:02:57,192
That's it, I think.

14
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:12,150
It hasn't really dawned upon me
that you're actually going.

15
00:03:12,320 --> 00:03:16,711
It doesn't strike you
until the goodbyes.

16
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:23,831
I've spent months trying to figure it
out, and I gave up. I just don't get it.

17
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:27,037
You could say it's like football.

18
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:31,034
You learn so and so much
through practice -

19
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:36,354
- but you learn more
by playing matches.

20
00:03:36,760 --> 00:03:42,232
- You also enjoy the comradeship.
- Of course. That's part of it.

21
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:48,873
- It's a challenge and an adventure ...
- And that's what hurts!

22
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:54,160
- An adventure? I can't ...
- But I want the experience.

23
00:04:55,760 --> 00:04:59,435
What's up?
Did you get home, or what?

24
00:05:00,680 --> 00:05:03,399
No ...
I'm here now.

25
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:11,115
Thanks for calling.
Bye.

26
00:05:12,040 --> 00:05:16,352
What a trendy hairstyle, Kim!
Not bad at all.

27
00:05:16,520 --> 00:05:23,790
- Is that our own logo?
- No. It says "Spearhead."

28
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:31,275
The Asian guy with the T-shirt ...

29
00:05:31,440 --> 00:05:34,750
- He's the medic in my group.
- Okay?

30
00:05:34,920 --> 00:05:38,754
- What does he do?
- Patches us up, if necessary.

31
00:05:38,920 --> 00:05:44,870
- Does he go on patrol with you?
- Oh, I see. Yes, he does.

32
00:05:45,920 --> 00:05:49,674
- I think I'll head upstairs.
- Okay.

33
00:05:49,840 --> 00:05:52,752
See you, Mom.

34
00:05:55,160 --> 00:05:58,994
- Goodbye.
- Behave yourself.

35
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,629
I want you to make sure -

36
00:06:31,800 --> 00:06:36,999
- that you pay attention
to your surroundings.

37
00:06:37,160 --> 00:06:40,914
Even if you think
it's safe and sound.

38
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:45,631
Forget about yourself
and what you look like.

39
00:06:49,320 --> 00:06:53,199
- I'm going to miss you.
- I'll miss you, too.

40
00:06:53,360 --> 00:06:55,920
- I love you.
- I know.

41
00:06:56,080 --> 00:06:58,958
- See you.
- Take care.

42
00:06:59,120 --> 00:07:00,758
See you.

43
00:07:00,920 --> 00:07:03,354
Bye, Dad.

44
00:07:03,520 --> 00:07:07,513
- See you.
- I'll hold you to that, Mads.

45
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:12,116
- Promise?
- I promise.

46
00:08:53,280 --> 00:08:55,953
Welcome. Welcome.

47
00:08:56,120 --> 00:09:00,159
- Did you have a good trip?
- It was a bit long.

48
00:09:00,320 --> 00:09:02,788
We haven't been bored
in Armadillo.

49
00:09:02,960 --> 00:09:04,916
400 shells were fired yesterday.

50
00:09:05,080 --> 00:09:07,514
- It was fairly ...
- 400?

51
00:09:07,720 --> 00:09:13,909
A Taliban mortar fired on us,
and we sent off 260120 mm -

52
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:17,032
- and 120105 mm.

53
00:09:17,200 --> 00:09:21,239
Air support and Apaches
were called in. It wasn't boring.

54
00:09:21,400 --> 00:09:26,235
The Taliban are much more
on their toes than I had thought.

55
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:32,839
They are just 800m away
from Armadillo and on the ball.

56
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:39,678
- So we'll confront them fairly soon.
- It's good there's work for us.

57
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:46,234
You can count on some action.
I promise it'll be interesting.

58
00:09:48,200 --> 00:09:51,556
Six months without women.

59
00:09:51,720 --> 00:09:55,315
- You're awfully cheerful.
- After a long night.

60
00:09:57,960 --> 00:10:01,157
- You have M&Ms?
- Hands off. It's my dinner.

61
00:10:01,320 --> 00:10:04,357
- Your dinner?
- What's your problem?

62
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:08,557
Mini wears size 3 in jackets.

63
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:12,679
Is that why his helmet says
"King of the Green Zone"?

64
00:10:26,560 --> 00:10:31,315
Welcome. Grab some water.
I have a few pointers.

65
00:10:31,480 --> 00:10:36,076
Gun line is shooting.
That's why it's so noisy.

66
00:10:36,240 --> 00:10:40,950
If you hear what sounds like a
rocket, it's the launchers firing.

67
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:44,192
It's fired at any time of the day.

68
00:10:44,360 --> 00:10:47,670
There was one. That's normal.

69
00:10:47,840 --> 00:10:50,513
Here are the shower containers.

70
00:10:52,600 --> 00:10:56,036
That's the Green Zone.
Observe as much as possible.

71
00:10:56,200 --> 00:10:59,510
When there's combat,
you're obviously more exposed -

72
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:02,513
- so don't just stand there staring.

73
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:07,071
"Walk-ins" stop just over there
and call for an interpreter.

74
00:11:07,240 --> 00:11:11,233
It doesn't take long to figure out
if they're dicking around -

75
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:13,630
- or if it's something useful.

76
00:11:19,560 --> 00:11:22,632
- You had some questions.
- Yes.

77
00:11:22,800 --> 00:11:28,033
How far north
from Armadillo can we go -

78
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:31,033
- before the Taliban get active?

79
00:11:31,200 --> 00:11:34,715
About 800-1000m
north of Armadillo.

80
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:39,317
From up here we can draw a line
almost up to the Helmand River.

81
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:43,632
This area here is basically ours.

82
00:11:43,800 --> 00:11:48,112
His objective is to move south
and isolate us so we can't get out -

83
00:11:48,280 --> 00:11:53,877
- and to diminish our influence on
the locals. That's what he wants to do.

84
00:11:54,040 --> 00:12:01,116
Our patrolling forces him to meet us
here and fight in this narrow pass.

85
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:06,035
These people are former mujahedeen
and used to fight the Russians -

86
00:12:06,200 --> 00:12:12,309
- in the exact same area, so they're
used to fighting a superior force.

87
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:17,235
They're not afraid.
Ten men might attack forty.

88
00:12:17,400 --> 00:12:21,916
Being outnumbered doesn't
stop them. Not at all.

89
00:12:22,080 --> 00:12:24,958
- They've got big balls
- That's for sure.

90
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:30,478
Did you treat the ones who were killed
and wounded in December?

91
00:12:30,640 --> 00:12:37,034
Unfortunately me and J were the ones
who found the dead on 12-19.

92
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:41,751
We were first on the spot. I grabbed
a detector and started sweeping.

93
00:12:41,920 --> 00:12:48,553
As we went around the vehicle, the
fucking beam from my headlamp -

94
00:12:48,720 --> 00:12:54,590
- caught this guy right in his face.
He was staring, but dead, of course.

95
00:12:54,760 --> 00:12:58,673
I closed his eyes
and covered up his face.

96
00:12:58,840 --> 00:13:01,877
And the last guy ...
There wasn't much left of him.

97
00:13:02,040 --> 00:13:06,113
I collected body parts for six hours.
Everything.

98
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:12,031
Fingers, a hand in a glove,
a knee joint, a heart lying around ...

99
00:13:12,200 --> 00:13:16,113
It's hard to describe what
it looks like in a place like that.

100
00:13:16,280 --> 00:13:19,272
You also have to
keep an eye on yourself.

101
00:13:19,440 --> 00:13:24,639
You're not wacko, just because
you laugh at some irrelevant stuff.

102
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:29,749
You need normality, 'cause this is so
meaningless that you can't grasp it.

103
00:13:31,840 --> 00:13:34,513
- <i>Susanne speaking.</i>
- Hi, it's Mads.

104
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:39,151
Hi, Mads.
I was hoping it was you.

105
00:13:39,320 --> 00:13:43,632
- How are you?
- <i>Fine, How about you?</i>

106
00:13:43,800 --> 00:13:46,598
That's much more interesting.

107
00:13:46,760 --> 00:13:51,880
- I'm fine. We're in Armadillo.
- <i>Okay.</i>

108
00:13:53,040 --> 00:13:58,273
- What's Dad up to?
- <i>He sitting right here.</i>

109
00:13:58,440 --> 00:14:01,796
I'll let you talk to him.

110
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:08,959
- <i>Hi, Mads.</i>
- Hi, Dad. How are you?

111
00:14:09,120 --> 00:14:11,759
We're fine, Mads.

112
00:14:11,920 --> 00:14:18,234
But yesterday
your mother had a fright -

113
00:14:18,400 --> 00:14:23,110
- when the phone rang
in the middle of the night.

114
00:14:23,280 --> 00:14:29,958
I didn't hear it, but she did.
It scared the daylights out of her.

115
00:14:30,120 --> 00:14:35,911
Your first thought is that
something terrible has happened.

116
00:14:36,080 --> 00:14:42,792
But it was a business call from India
about something they're printing -

117
00:14:42,960 --> 00:14:46,509
- and they forgot
about the time difference.

118
00:14:53,840 --> 00:14:58,789
Since we left Denmark,
the enemy's objective hasn't changed.

119
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:04,114
The Taliban's objective is
to destabilize security in Helmand -

120
00:15:04,280 --> 00:15:08,512
- and undermine the locals' trust
in the ISAF forces.

121
00:15:10,200 --> 00:15:15,354
It's important to get
into Haftaran and Athakhan -

122
00:15:15,520 --> 00:15:20,753
- to establish contact with the people.
When you eat your field rations -

123
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:24,435
- and there's something
you don't like -

124
00:15:24,600 --> 00:15:27,990
- I suggest you save it
and bring it on patrol.

125
00:15:28,160 --> 00:15:33,473
Give it to the children
as a sign of good will.

126
00:15:34,320 --> 00:15:36,038
Rules of engagement.

127
00:15:36,200 --> 00:15:39,988
Remember that self defense
can apply prior to being fired upon.

128
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:46,633
Such as by confirmed weapons or
people moving into a position to fire.

129
00:15:47,480 --> 00:15:50,438
Yes. Go get ready.

130
00:15:50,600 --> 00:15:57,790
Listen up. Line up, so 6-5 can take
our picture before our first patrol.

131
00:16:59,200 --> 00:17:02,078
I don't have anything.

132
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:27,190
I can see why the Wadis
are dangerous.

133
00:17:27,360 --> 00:17:33,310
They can easily hide an IED.
The thought is sickening.

134
00:17:33,480 --> 00:17:38,429
We're most likely to go around it -

135
00:17:38,600 --> 00:17:41,558
- so it would be stupid
to put one here.

136
00:17:48,760 --> 00:17:52,673
905, I saw a man run through
the fence on the eastern side -

137
00:17:52,840 --> 00:17:59,837
- of the row of bushes
that run from north to south.

138
00:18:23,240 --> 00:18:25,708
Welcome to Nam.

139
00:18:27,320 --> 00:18:31,632
- Hey, interpreter!
- Follow me. Come.

140
00:18:31,800 --> 00:18:36,396
Hayatullah, hurry.
Don't let them onto the poppy field.

141
00:18:36,560 --> 00:18:42,874
This way. Not in the field.
I will show you.

142
00:18:44,240 --> 00:18:50,759
9-0 here. Civilians are showing us
the route around the field.

143
00:19:08,600 --> 00:19:11,068
Salaam aleikum.

144
00:19:11,240 --> 00:19:15,028
How are you? Alright?

145
00:19:15,200 --> 00:19:19,716
- Read your book.
- Are you reading? Yes.

146
00:19:21,600 --> 00:19:25,479
- It's a madrassa.
- Are you studying the Koran?

147
00:19:25,640 --> 00:19:29,269
- Have things been calm?
- How is the situation in the area?

148
00:19:29,440 --> 00:19:33,479
- Calm?
- No, where is it safe?

149
00:19:33,640 --> 00:19:39,431
- Are the Taliban in the area?
- They've taken the whole area.

150
00:19:39,600 --> 00:19:42,672
How could you not know?
They're everywhere.

151
00:19:42,840 --> 00:19:45,957
Tell us if you see anything.

152
00:19:46,120 --> 00:19:49,351
So we can get them out
of the area.

153
00:19:49,520 --> 00:19:52,114
We cannot cooperate with you.

154
00:19:52,280 --> 00:19:56,751
You come with all your weapons,
and then you leave.

155
00:19:56,920 --> 00:20:00,833
We're staying here, and then the
Taliban will come after us.

156
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:05,198
But if you don't cooperate,
we cannot secure the area -

157
00:20:05,360 --> 00:20:08,909
- and then we can't build
a school for your kids.

158
00:20:13,240 --> 00:20:18,234
You have guns, they have guns.
If I talk, they'll cut my throat.

159
00:20:32,200 --> 00:20:36,159
- First patrol reporting!
- Look at my back!

160
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:40,639
Look cool, man!

161
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:46,110
Just a sec.

162
00:20:47,080 --> 00:20:49,878
First patrol reporting.

163
00:20:50,040 --> 00:20:54,272
It didn't feel like anything.
Not really.

164
00:20:56,120 --> 00:20:59,635
I probably will,
when we get into the shooting.

165
00:20:59,800 --> 00:21:04,237
But this is also part of it.
It's not all fighting.

166
00:21:04,400 --> 00:21:08,951
Right, we're also here
to help these poor people.

167
00:21:09,120 --> 00:21:13,989
It's like going to the fun fair
without trying the roller-coasters.

168
00:21:16,040 --> 00:21:18,679
Alright, let's start the debriefing.

169
00:21:18,840 --> 00:21:21,513
The patrol itself. How did it go?

170
00:21:24,920 --> 00:21:29,914
Individual skills really sucked.
Seriously.

171
00:21:30,080 --> 00:21:33,868
How many fell to their knees
on short stops?

172
00:21:36,640 --> 00:21:39,712
So, eight men out of 50.

173
00:21:39,880 --> 00:21:42,952
Do we agree that
this has to be improved?

174
00:21:43,120 --> 00:21:49,275
Get into the habit now.
Get your fat ass down on its knees -

175
00:21:49,440 --> 00:21:53,194
- because at some point
if you don't, then pow!

176
00:21:53,360 --> 00:21:58,309
So kneel, damn it!
Right. Anything else?

177
00:21:58,480 --> 00:22:04,032
I think I ought to say what I got out
of this patrol. And it wasn't a lot.

178
00:22:04,200 --> 00:22:07,510
Remember this is an agricultural area.

179
00:22:07,680 --> 00:22:12,435
The peasants have just sown their
wheat. And we're ploughing it down.

180
00:22:12,600 --> 00:22:17,469
I could only say that our security out
there was to trample their fields down.

181
00:22:46,920 --> 00:22:51,675
Nothing's happening out there yet.

182
00:22:51,840 --> 00:22:56,868
The good old classic. The coolest
thing about porn is the story line.

183
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:05,795
I'd like doctors like that,
if I go to hospital.

184
00:23:18,160 --> 00:23:21,470
Strangely enough it helped him!

185
00:23:31,840 --> 00:23:37,756
It's weird, don't you think?
You volunteer to sleep on a tiny cot -

186
00:23:37,920 --> 00:23:40,798
- and eat crap food for six months.

187
00:23:43,360 --> 00:23:49,151
- I know there's more to it.
- I'm doing it for the team spirit.

188
00:23:49,320 --> 00:23:52,676
- Team spirit and adventure.
- Yeah.

189
00:23:52,840 --> 00:23:56,594
- How do your parents feel about it?
- They're not overjoyed.

190
00:23:56,760 --> 00:24:01,311
"Don't go on missions." -

191
00:24:01,480 --> 00:24:06,918
So I decided to go to Kosovo,
and on my first day at the garrison -

192
00:24:07,080 --> 00:24:11,437
- I still thought
I was going to Kosovo.

193
00:24:11,600 --> 00:24:17,550
But at the meeting we were told
that Kosovo wasn't an option.

194
00:24:17,760 --> 00:24:22,993
Here it's all 'Afghan'.
I called my mother afterwards -

195
00:24:23,160 --> 00:24:27,711
- and told her I was going
to Afghanistan after all.

196
00:24:27,880 --> 00:24:29,791
She cried her eyes out.

197
00:24:32,440 --> 00:24:36,069
Fucking hell, Rasmus.
What time is it?

198
00:24:36,240 --> 00:24:39,630
- 41 minutes past.
- What's this? A little mullah?

199
00:24:41,920 --> 00:24:46,994
- Are those animals? Two foxes?
- They sure aren't hedgehogs.

200
00:24:50,880 --> 00:24:53,110
What the hell was that?

201
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:59,312
- Was that mortars?
- Call in and find out.

202
00:25:01,240 --> 00:25:03,276
You know what's going on?
Over.

203
00:25:03,440 --> 00:25:06,238
I have a good idea.
I'll just check it out.

204
00:25:06,400 --> 00:25:12,191
It's probably the person digging
from before that we engaged. Over.

205
00:25:14,960 --> 00:25:19,033
It's cool they bombed the idiot.
Too bad we can't see him.

206
00:25:32,600 --> 00:25:36,354
You'll be an easy target now.

207
00:25:51,880 --> 00:25:57,034
- It's doing a recce.
- Nice.

208
00:25:57,200 --> 00:26:00,192
It's our eyes out there.

209
00:26:00,360 --> 00:26:05,832
It's cool that it can check out
suspicious things in a compound.

210
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:07,353
Right.

211
00:26:14,200 --> 00:26:18,079
I'd like to see some action now.

212
00:26:18,240 --> 00:26:22,677
I don't know
what my first reaction will be.

213
00:26:22,840 --> 00:26:27,868
We haven't got a chance to know what
it's like, when we haven't tried it.

214
00:26:28,040 --> 00:26:33,433
And the thought of these
'foreign fighters', you know.

215
00:26:33,600 --> 00:26:39,630
I can imagine that the first contact
will be rather spicy.

216
00:26:46,040 --> 00:26:48,156
He could be Taliban.

217
00:26:52,160 --> 00:26:57,188
Just like anyone
of the 7 billion people out there.

218
00:26:57,360 --> 00:27:02,309
- Too bad we can't tell them apart.
- The only difference is the weapon.

219
00:27:02,480 --> 00:27:07,031
He could be hiding it
under his clothes.

220
00:27:07,200 --> 00:27:11,796
But it's clever.
Imagine we could do the same.

221
00:27:11,960 --> 00:27:14,633
Do you think anyone
is watching us?

222
00:27:14,800 --> 00:27:18,315
- Someone's always watching us.
- Right.

223
00:27:18,480 --> 00:27:22,268
There's bound to be someone
in these compounds -

224
00:27:22,440 --> 00:27:26,592
- who is on the Taliban side
and keeps an eye on us.

225
00:27:28,920 --> 00:27:31,878
What are you seeing?

226
00:27:33,120 --> 00:27:35,588
What does he want?

227
00:27:41,480 --> 00:27:44,119
What now, Billy Bob?

228
00:27:47,840 --> 00:27:49,831
Hang on a sec.

229
00:28:02,880 --> 00:28:04,836
- Who?
- This guy.

230
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:08,310
- Is it the informer?
- No, he's lighting a cigarette.

231
00:28:08,480 --> 00:28:11,153
They don't always do that.

232
